<br>
For what it's worth, I quit, and I'm not planning on coming back anytime soon.<br>
<br>
I played a lot of EQ, too.  Not as much as some people here, but my mage was level 60, almost had his arch title, and had 130+ days played.  It wasn't uncommon for me to do 12 hour days starting early in the morning and ending whenever my guild quit raiding that night.  I'm unemployed and not going to school, I didn't have a whole lot else to do with my time.  There was even a point in time where I played EQ instead of going to school.<br>
<br>
Despite that, I never considered myself <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>addicted</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, and I don't attribute my failure to finish high school on Everquest.  I played Everquest because I chose not to go to school; I didn't choose not to go to school so I could play Everquest.  EQ was just something I did to fill my time -- time that could've been better spent doing something else, granted, but it's not like I was going to do those things anyway. :)<br>
<br>
It bothered me when people said I was addicted to the game.  I'd reply, &quot;No, I'm not.  If I ever feel that I need to leave, I'll just stop playing.&quot;  They'd laugh and tell me I wouldn't last two days.<br>
<br>
Well...  The mage changes, the PoP rebalancing, the additional levels and skills, the fact that I need to find a decent job and move out on my own, as well as a number of other personal issues... It was enough.  I thought, &quot;I need to stop playing EQ now.&quot;<br>
<br>
And I did.<br>
<br>
And I have no desire or intention to come back. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub102.ezboard.com/bthemagicianstower.showUserPublicProfile?gid=rhionsligo>rhionsligo</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Sage</span><br>  Posts: 1190<br> <font color=#333333>(11/10/02 3:34:19 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowergeneral.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=7809.topic&index=16>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.lehigh.edu/~dsf3/EQ/starofdavid.gif width=36 height=37></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Eh.</span><hr size=1> I honestly feel sorry for the large majority of people in the world who have not found their <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>&quot;EverQuest&quot;</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> in life - something they enjoy doing a whole lot and can do it whenever they want.  People who have not found that thing in life sit around bored, turn to drugs/crime, think about only sex all day, are frustrated with life, etc.  I know that any time I want, I can log on to EverQuest and enjoy myself.  Other people...well, they go do something and pray that they have a good time.<br>
